default Can 
defaultthe G
defaultovernment confirm that it intends to apply the ‘indexed deduction’ method to adjusting the block grant for the 
defaultintroduction of devolved income
default? 
default What information can it supply about the impact of applying that reduction to the Welsh block grant?  
defaultIf an element of income tax is devolved following a referendum, the Government intends to apply the ‘indexed deduction’ mechanism to adjust the Welsh Government block grant as recommended by the Silk Commission (and which is also being implemented in Scotland).  
defaultIn the first year of operating this mechanism (as well as in any preceding transitional years) an amount equivalent to the revenues generated by the Welsh rate of income tax (at 10p) will be deducted from the block grant.  If the Welsh Government sets a rate of 10p then its budget will be unchanged during these years (as the deduction will be the same as the revenues generated by the Welsh rate of income tax). Setting a Welsh rate of 11p or 9p will lead to a higher or lower budget respectively (as the deduction will still be based on the 10p forfeited by the UK Government).  
defaultIn year 2 onwards, the deduction from the previous year will be indexed against growth in the UK non savings non dividend (NSND) 
defaultincome tax base,
default  
defaulti
default.e. if the UK NSND income tax base grows by, for example, 1% or -5%, then so will the deduction. The Welsh Government budget will therefore benefit from these new arrangements when the NSND income tax base grows more quickly in Wales than the UK average (and conversely the budget will be lower if growth is slower).  
defaultBy linking the Welsh Government budget to the performance of the Welsh economy, this increases accountability and provides a further incentive to create growth.  But at the same time this mechanism shields the Welsh Government budget from UK-wide effects that the UK Government is better placed to manage (as the Welsh Government budget is only affected by the relative performance of the Welsh and UK NSND income tax base).
default4. 
defaultWhat approaches will be used to calculate 
defaultreductions
default from the block grant for stamp duty land tax and landfill tax?  
defaultThe UK and Scottish Governments are currently discussing the most appropriate block grant adjustment mechanism in relation to stamp duty land tax and landfill tax.  The Scotland Bill Command Paper indicated that this would be a one-off adjustment but the precise nature of that adjustment is still to be agreed.  
defaultThe UK Government has now opened similar discussions with the Welsh Government, with the intention that the same mechanism can be agreed for both Wales and Scotland.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe
default definition of a Scottish taxpayer inserted by the
default Scotland Act 2012 
defaultsets out that,
default 
defaulti
defaultf an individual has a main place of residence for the same amount of time, or spends the same number of days, in Scotland as in another part of the 
defaultUK;
default they will be a Scottish taxpayer. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis means that the definition of a Welsh taxpayer cannot be identically drafted to the parallel provision in Scotland, as this would mean a taxpayer could be both a Welsh and Scottish taxpayer in the same year
default if
default,
default for example, their main place of residence was in each country for an equal amount of time.
default  
default&#xa0;
defaultOptions to resolve thi
defaults issue are currently being considered
default and will be included in the final Bill.
