 Assembly passed before the amendment comes into force, ordefault(b) the previous or continuing operation of such an Act of the Assembly.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultCHAPTER 2default&#xa0;defaultINCOME TAXdefault&#xa0;
default116C Power to set Welsh rate for Welsh taxpayersdefault&#xa0;default(1) Thedefault Assembly may by resolution (a “Welsh rate resolution”default) set the Welsh rate for the purpose of calculating the rates of income tax to be paid by Welsh taxpayers.default&#xa0;default(2) Section 6(2B) of the Income Tax Act 2007 provides for the calculation of those rates.default&#xa0;default(3) A Welsh rate resolution applies–default(a) for only one tax year, anddefault(b) for the whole of that year.default&#xa0;default(4) A Welsh rate resolution may specify only one rate.default&#xa0;default(5) The Welsh rate must be a whole number or half a whole number.default&#xa0;default(6) A Welsh rate resolution–default(a) must specify the tax year for which it applies,default(b) must be made before the start of that tax year, anddefault(c) must not be made more than 12 months before the start of that year.default&#xa0;default(7) If a Welsh rate resolution is cancelled before the start of the tax year for which it is to apply–default(a) the Income Tax Acts have effect for that year as if the resolution had never been passed, anddefault(b) the resolution may be replaced by another Welsh rate resolution.default&#xa0;default(8) The standing orders must provide that only the First Minister or a Welsh Minister appointed under section 48 may move a motion for a Welsh rate resolution.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default116D Welsh taxpayersdefault&#xa0;default(1) In any tax year, a Welsh taxpayer is an individual (T) who, for that year–default(a) is resident in the defaultUKdefault for income tax purposes (see Schedule 45 to the Finance Act 2013), anddefault(b) meets condition A, B or C.default&#xa0;default(2) T meets condition A if T has a close connection with defaultWalesdefault (see section 116E).default&#xa0;default(3) T meets condition B ifdefault–default(a) T does not have a close connection with defaultEnglanddefault, defaultScotlanddefault or defaultNorthern Irelanddefault (see section 116E), anddefault(b) T spends more days of that year in defaultWalesdefault than in any other part of the defaultUKdefault (see section 116F).default&#xa0;default(4) T meets condition C if, for the whole or any part of the year, T is–default(a) a member of Parliament for a constituency in defaultWalesdefault,default(b) a member of the European Parliament for defaultWalesdefault, ordefault(c) an Assembly member.default&#xa0;default(5) In this Chapter “the defaultUKdefault”default means the defaultUnited Kingdomdefault.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default116E Close connection with defaultWalesdefault or another part of the defaultUKdefault&#xa0;default(1) To find whether, for any year, T has a close connection with any part of the defaultUKdefault see–default(a) subsection (2) (where T has only one place of residence in the defaultUKdefault), ordefault(b) subsection (3) (where T has 2 or more places of residence in the defaultUKdefault).default&#xa0;default(2) T has a close connection with a part of the defaultUKdefault if in that year–default(a) T has only one place of residence in the defaultUKdefault,default(b) that place of residence is in that part of the defaultUKdefault, anddefault(c) for at least part of the year, T lives at that place.default&#xa0;default(3) T has a close connection with a part of the defaultUKdefault if in that year–default(a) T has 2 or more places of residence in the defaultUKdefault,default(b) for at least part of the year, T’s main place of residence in the defaultUKdefault is in that part of the defaultUKdefault,default(c) the times in the year when T’s main place of residence is in that part of the UK comprise (in aggregate) at least as much of the year asdefault defaultthe times when T’s main place of residence is in any one other part of the UK, anddefault(d) for at least part of the year, T lives at a place of residence in that part of the defaultUKdefault.default&#xa0;
default(4) In this section “place” includes a place on board a vessel or other means of transport.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default116F Days spent in defaultWalesdefault or another part of the defaultUKdefault&#xa0;default(1) T spends more days of a year in defaultWalesdefault than in any other part of the defaultUKdefault if (and only if) –default(a) the number of days in the year on which T is in defaultWalesdefault at the end of the day equals or exceedsdefault(b) the number of days in the year on which T is in any other part of the defaultUKdefault at the end of the day.default&#xa0;default(2) But T is not to be treated as being in the defaultUKdefault at the end of a day if–default(a) on that day T arrives in the defaultUKdefault as a passenger,default(b) T departs from the defaultUKdefault on the next day, anddefault(c) during the time between arrival and departure T does not engage in activities which are to a substantial extent unrelated to T’s passage through the defaultUKdefault.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default116G Supplemental powers to modify enactmentsdefault&#xa0;default(1) The Treasury may by order provide that subsections (2A), (2B) and (2D) of section 6 of the Income Tax Act 2007 are to be disapplied, or that their effect is to be modified, in relation to any enactment.default&#xa0;default(2) The Treasury may by order make such modifications of any enactment as they consider necessary or expedient in consequence of or in connection with–default(a) the power of the Assembly to set a rate under section 116C;default(b) the making of a Welsh rate resolution;default(c) an order under subsection (1).default&#xa0;default(3) An order under subsection (2) may, in particular, provide that a Welsh rate resolution does not require any change in the amounts repayable or deductible under PAYE regulations between–default(a) the beginning of the tax year for which the resolution has effect, anddefault(b) such date (falling after the date of the resolution) as may 